<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-05T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-05T17:00:00-05:00" n="147" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d147">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112A/1855u</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Representatives in Latin
                                        American Countries</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Circular telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-05T18:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 5, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Inexpediency of publishing certain names eligible for enemy trading
                                list necessitates a confidential enemy trading list. In recommending
                                additions and removals confidential list confer British, French,
                                Italian colleagues and proceed as in case recommendations published
                                enemy trading list. Specific reasons within scope Trading with Enemy
                                Act should be given in recommendations for addition <pb facs="0198" n="1032" xml:id="pg_1032"/> to enemy trading list or
                                confidential list. Desirable to unify Allied confidential lists far
                                as possible. Fictitious names and names of men of straw used merely
                                to cloak enemy trade should be recommended for inclusion in cloaks
                                list and not enemy trading list, indicating name of principal as
                                well. No established firm should be listed in cloaks list for
                                cloaking enemy trade, but should be recommended for published or
                                confidential enemy trading list.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>